I'd be interested to know what y'all make of the effects on Blots of
the Pragmatic Currencies Proposal. This might help to shed new light
on the Mint Manipulation issue...

The new Rule 1435 would redefine a Blot thus : "A Payment Order for
1 Indulgence, the payee of which is the Bank, is called a Blot.".

First observation :

If it is indeed the case that Payment Orders are not Nomic Entities,
then we'd have to conclude that Rule 1586 would apply in this case,
and that any Blots held by Players prior to the adoption of P/C would
be destroyed upon adoption, always assuming that it _is_ adopted, of
course. If at this juncture Blots cease to be NEs, then there is no
longer any Nomic Entity that is a Blot defined by the Rules, and, by
Rule 1586, all previous such Entities are destroyed.

I do not think it matters much that Blots are 'aliased', so to speak,
with an amount of -1 Indulgences; they are nevertheless a Nomic Entity,
and Rule 1586 seems to apply, calling for the destruction of every
negative amount of Indulgences. Weirdness...

Second observation:

It makes little sense to think of a Blot, even in the new framework,
and the above notwithstanding, as _not_ being an Entity existing solely
by virtue of the Rules defining it to exist.

The previous (well, present) situation wrt Blots, IMHO, argues against
Steve's notion that we can gain better understanding of how Nomic
Entities are manipulated by equating them to poker chips. Say
Indulgences are blue chips; what are Blots ? I guess it would be
silly to argue that a Blot is minus one blue chip; for the poker chip
analogy to be useful, we'd have to imagine that a Blot is a red chip,
and that what actually happens when one receives a Blot is that one
is given a red chip, and that whenever someone has got a red chip and
at least one blue chip, e is supposed to return a red and a blue to
the pile. Players who have only red chips... well, as I said, Steve's
metaphor does not necessarily gain us much understanding - it requires
two distinct entities for positive and negative amounts of anything
that is a _single_ Nomic Entity. But it's perhaps interesting to
also apply it to Blots _after_ P/C.

There still is an Entity manipulated in this Game after the adoption
of P/C that is known as a Blot. Players receive them, amounts of them
are named as penalties. Rule 1435 states that when a Player gains Blots,
Payment Orders are executed; and that a Player "may be said to have"
a number of Blots equal to the amount of Indulgences assessed against
em. Going back to poker chips: in a face-to-face game, we'd probably go
on using reds to represent Blots. One could gain red chips, but the only
way one could get rid of one would be to satisfy a PO for one Indulgence.
The way to do that, of course, would be to give one blue chip to the
Bank...

Thus my next argument to support the notion that the M-Currencies can
be somehow - to what extent I don't know - conflated with POs and TOs
as defined by the Rules enacted by P/C : these very Rules come very
close themselves to equating POs and TOs to something that I doubt
very much is _not_ a Nomic Entity, the Blot.


