That is itself sufficient to make it a NE, IMHO. In fact, if "a Blot is an
instance of a type of Entity E", as you assert, we should be able to shorten
that to "a Blot is an E". We don't after all go around saying "I transfer one 
instance of the Entity type P-Note to Player X" do we ?

OK, let's go at this in a systematic fashion. We are debating whether a Blot
is an entity, in the generic sense, or not. An entity is, basically, something
that is. (The Latin root verb for the word is "to be".) So IMHO as long as
anything called X which in some way or another has any abstract or concrete
existence, we can point to that and say, "X is an entity". What matters as far 
as Rule 1586 is concerned is whether that entity owes its existence solely to 
the Rules, or not.

