Klaus Herrmanns NB6_25 (3751) writes:
>
>But playing in the virtual world we need means to avoid
>counterfeiting, stealing and other unwanted things - they could not
>only occur bacause of intentional cheating, but also "by accident" as
>communications are lost, inconsistently tracked etc. And that is more
>complicated because virtual currency is so much easier to create or
>manipulate in ways not provided for by the rules than a one inch
>plastic token.

I think this assertion is mistaken, and I think the mistake arises
out of a confusion about abstraction. Basically, I believe that
because bits of information are in one sense more abstract than
plastic poker chips, some people have come to believe that the
entities they represent are abstract in a quite different - 
mathematical - sense. I believe this to be a mistake. Bits of
information are still physical and still governed by physical laws,
albeit by a different part of physical law than that which governs
the movements of poker chips.

I actually think that it is much *more* difficult to manipulate
virtual currencies in ways not provided for by the Rules. Plastic
poker chips are easy to steal: just wait until the Player is
distracted or goes to the bathroom or whatever and take one.
On the other hand, although it is possible to perform an analogous
feat for virtual currencies, it is quite difficult: you'd have to
hack a whole bunch of files containing the records of currency
holdings. I'm pretty certain that no-one has ever attempted this.
However, it's only R1011 that makes it illegal. Otherwise, R116 would
permit it.

The point is that what you can't do is steal virtual currencies
simply by posting to the Public Forum "I hereby steal 5 VTs from
Morendil." We used to explain this by saying that such an action
was permissible, but not possible. My recent thinking on the subject
leads me to qualify that explanation: actually, it *is* possible 
(because the records are encoded as physical bits of information
which it is perfectly possible to manipulate - illegally - according
to physical law), it's just not possible merely by posting to the
PF. Similarly, in a face-to-face game, you can't steal poker chips
by announcing to the room at large, "I hereby steal 5 VTs from
Morendil"; you actually have to take some physical action which
results in a change to the distribution of the physical tokens being
used to represent VTs. 

The fact that this maxim applies equally to face-to-face games as to
email-based games is my reason for claiming that, metaphysically,
there's no real difference between the two kinds of games. The
metaphysical question is: what is the relationship between the
entities defined or referred to by the rules of the game and the
physical tokens used to represent the distribution of those entities?
Answering that question gives essentially the same picture for
Monopoly as it does for Agora, or so I claim. In each case, the 
rules of the game define the ways in which the physical tokens may
be legally manipulated. In addition there will (almost certainly)
be further - illegal - ways in which it is physically possible to
manipulate those tokens. In each case, questions about the actual
state of the game will be answered by referring to the distribution
of the physical tokens. Where there is disagreement about the legality
of some change in the distribution of the physical tokens, players
will usually refer back to the most recent state of the game which 
they are prepared to accept as legal - regardless of how that state
was arrived at - and work from there. In neither case is it possible
to change the distribution of physical tokens by fiat: physical
action appropriate to the kind of physical token being used to
represent the game entity (stealing chips, hacking files) will have
to be taken to achieve that end. The legality of such manipulations
is, as ever, decided by the rules of the game.



